1:100.name: Configuration=standard, State=enabled
1:100.description:
Standard Icon buttons are low-emphasis buttons.
They are used for the lowest priority actions, especially when presenting multiple options.

Icon buttons can be placed on a variety of backgrounds. Until the button is interacted with, its container isnt visible.

1:701.name: Style=outlined, State=enabled, Text configurations=label-text, Leading icon=false, Trailing icon=True

1:2187.name: Configuration=Filled, State=enabled, Show Icon=False
1:2187.description:
Filled buttons are high-emphasis buttons.
They have the most visual impact after the FAB, and should be used for important, final actions that complete a flow, like "Save", "Join now", or "Confirm".

6:2379.name: horizontal/full-width
6:2379.description:
Dividers are one way to visually group components and create hierarchy. They can also be used to imply nested parent/child relationships.

Use full width dividers to separate larger sections of unrelated content. They can be used directly on a surface or inside other components like cards or lists.

1:23.name: Icon button
1:23.description:
Icon buttons display actions in a compact layout. Icon buttons can represent opening actions such as opening an overflow menu or search, or represent binary actions that can be toggled on and off, such as favorite or bookmark.

Icon buttons can be grouped together or they can stand alone.

1:115.name: [m3:text-field] Text field
1:115.description:
Use a text field when someone needs to enter text into a UI, such as filling in contact or payment information.

 Additional options
Support text - you can toggle supporting text between hide and show.

1:2014.name: [m3:button] Button
1:2014.description: Buttons communicate actions that users can take. They are typically placed throughout your UI, in places like Dialogs, Modal windows, Forms, Cards and Toolbars

1:2230.name: [m3:checkbox] Checkboxes
1:2230.description: Checkboxes are a selection control which allow users to select one or more options from a set; present a list containing sub-selections; and turn an item on or off in a desktop environment

6:6797.name: [m3:list-item] List item/List Item: 0 Density
6:6797.description:
List items can contain primary and supplemental actions represented by text, a leading icon and/or a trailing icon

Density can be used in denser UIs where space is limited. Density is only applied to the height.

 Additional options 
List item - can be edited by selecting an individual list item and  selecting states, leading icons, trailing icons, and dividers from the variant properties.
